 {"id":"bd-mwff","title":"Implement join! macro","description":"# Task

Implement the `join!` macro for awaiting multiple handles concurrently.

## Syntax

```rust
// Tuple form
let (r1, r2, r3) = join!(h1, h2, h3);

// With cx for cancellation propagation
let (r1, r2, r3) = join!(cx, h1, h2, h3);

// Array form (all same type)
let results: [Outcome<i32, E>; 3] = join![h1, h2, h3];
```

## Expansion

```rust
// join!(h1, h2, h3)
// expands to:
{
    let __h1 = h1;
    let __h2 = h2;
    let __h3 = h3;
    // Use futures::join! or custom implementation
    let (__r1, __r2, __r3) = futures::join!(__h1, __h2, __h3);
    (__r1, __r2, __r3)
}

// join!(cx, h1, h2, h3)
// expands to:
cx.join((h1, h2, h3)).await
```

## Semantics (from formal semantics §5.1)

1. All handles are polled concurrently
2. If any handle returns Panicked, others are cancelled (fail-fast)
3. Results are returned as tuple matching input order
4. Aggregation uses severity lattice: Ok < Err < Cancelled < Panicked

## Implementation Notes

1. Parse optional cx
2. Parse comma-separated handles
3. Count handles for tuple size
4. Generate appropriate join call
5. Handle both tuple and array cases

## Error Handling

- "join! requires at least one handle"
- Type errors surfaced clearly for mismatched types in array form

## Tests

```rust
#[test]
fn join_all_ok() {
    Lab::new().run(|cx| async {
        scope!(cx, {
            let h1 = spawn!(scope, async { 1 });
            let h2 = spawn!(scope, async { 2 });
            let (r1, r2) = join!(h1, h2);
            assert_eq!(r1.unwrap(), 1);
            assert_eq!(r2.unwrap(), 2);
        });
    });
}

#[test]
fn join_one_error() {
    Lab::new().run(|cx| async {
        scope!(cx, {
            let h1 = spawn!(scope, async { Ok::<_, &str>(1) });
            let h2 = spawn!(scope, async { Err("oops") });
            let (r1, r2) = join!(h1, h2);
            // Both complete, r2 is error
        });
    });
}
```

